Convergence Analyses of Davis‚ÄìYin Splitting via Scaled Relative Graphs

Jongmin Lee‚Ä†‚Ä° ‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉ Soheun Yi¬ß‚Ä° ‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉ Ernest K.¬†Ryu‚Ä†
Abstract

Davis‚ÄìYin splitting (DYS) has found a wide range of applications in optimization, but its linear rates of convergence have not been studied extensively. The scaled relative graph (SRG) simplifies the convergence analysis of operator splitting methods by mapping the action of the operator to the complex plane, but the prior SRG theory did not fully apply to the DYS operator. In this work, we formalize an SRG theory for the DYS operator and use it to obtain tighter contraction factors.

keywords:
Convex optimization, Splitting methods, Monotone operators, Euclidean geometry
00footnotetext: ‚Ä†‚Ä†\dagger‚Ä†Department of Mathematical Sciences, Seoul National University.00footnotetext: ‚Ä°‚Ä°\ddagger‚Ä°Equal contribution.00footnotetext: ¬ß¬ß\S¬ßDepartment of Statistics and Data Science, Carnegie Mellon University.

1 Introduction

The Davis‚ÄìYin splitting (DYS) operator [18] encodes solutions of the three-operator monotone inclusion problem

findx‚àà‚Ñã0‚àà(++)x,\displaystyle\underset{x\in{\mathcal{H}}}{\text{find}}\quad 0\in({\varbbA}+{% \varbbB}+{\varbbC})x,start_UNDERACCENT italic_x ‚àà caligraphic_H end_UNDERACCENT start_ARG find end_ARG 0 ‚àà ( + + ) italic_x ,

where ‚Ñã‚Ñã{\mathcal{H}}caligraphic_H is a real Hilbert space, and are monotone, and is cocoercive, as fixed-points of the operator

=‚àí+Œ±(2‚àíŒ±‚àíŒ±)Œ±Œ±,{\varbbT}={\varbbI}-{}_{\alpha{\varbbB}}+{}_{\alpha{\varbbA}}(2{}_{\alpha{% \varbbB}}-{\varbbI}-\alpha{\varbbC}{}_{\alpha{\varbbB}}),= - start_FLOATSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ± end_FLOATSUBSCRIPT + start_FLOATSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ± end_FLOATSUBSCRIPT ( 2 start_FLOATSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ± end_FLOATSUBSCRIPT - - italic_Œ± start_FLOATSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ± end_FLOATSUBSCRIPT ) ,

where Œ±>0ùõº0\alpha>0italic_Œ± > 0 and Œ± and Œ± are the resolvents of and . DYS generalizes the forward-backward splitting (FBS) and Douglas‚ÄìRachford splitting (DRS) operators, and it has found a wide range of applications [48, 46, 7, 44, 47, 24] in optimization. However, linear convergence rates of DYS iterations have not been studied extensively.

On the other hand, the recently proposed scaled relative graph (SRG) [38] allows one to analyze the convergence of operator splitting methods by mapping the action of a multi-valued nonlinear operator to the extended complex plane, analogous to how the spectrum maps the action of a linear operator to the complex plane. Prior work used the SRG to analyze rates of convergence for FBS and DRS [38], but the prior SRG theory did not fully apply to the DYS operator.

In this paper, we analyze convergence rates of DYS iterations using the SRG. First, we extend the SRG theory to accommodate the DYS operator. We then establish linear rates of convergence of DYS by bounding the maximum modulus of the SRG on the complex plane. We furthermore provide a new result on averagedness coefficients of DYS.

1.1 Prior Works

Splitting methods for monotone inclusion problems is a powerful framework encompassing a wide range of convex optimization algorithms [2, 37, 40]. Classical splitting methods such as forward-backward splitting (FBS) [6, 30, 3], Douglas‚ÄìRachford splitting (DRS) [32, 19, 28], and alternating directions method of multipliers (ADMM) [21, 22], a derived splitting algorithm, have had an enormous range of applications. As a splitting scheme unifying FBS and DRS, Generalized forward-backward splitting (GFBS) [36] was first proposed, and Forward-Douglas‚ÄìRachford splitting (FDRS) [5] was then presented as an extension of GFBS. In 2017, Davis and Yin proposed what we call the Davis-Yin splitting (DYS) as a complete unification of FBS and DRS [18]. This breakthrough has found a wide range of new applications [48, 46, 7, 44, 47, 24] and many variants of DYS such as stochastic DYS [49, 51, 8, 50, 34], inexact DYS [52], adaptive DYS [35], inertial DYS [15], and primal-dual DYS[41] have been proposed.

However, the study of linear convergence rates of DYS has been limited. Bredies, Chenchene, Lorenz, and Naldi studied the convergence of DYS under a wider range of stepsizes [4] and Arag√≥n-Artacho and Torregrosa-Bel√©n also proved the convergence of the DYS iteration over a wider range of stepsizes [1]. Dao and Phan analyzed a modified version of DYS iterations [16], and Pedregosa analyzed sublinear convergence rates of DYS iterations [33], but they did not analyze linear rates of convergence. Condat and Richt√°rik analyzed linear convergence rates of a randomized version of Primal-Dual Davis‚ÄìYin (PDDY) [14]. Ryu, Taylor, Bergeling, and Giselsson [39] and Wang, Fazlyab, Chen, and Preciado [45] formulated the problem of computing tight contraction factors as SDPs using the performance estimation problem (PEP) and integral quadratic constraint (IQC) approaches, but these are numerical results, not analytic convergence proofs in the classical sense. To the best of our knowledge, the only prior works providing analytic linear convergence rates of DYS iterations are the arXiv version of the original DYS paper [18] and [14]. The latter work [14] considers randomized updates, which makes the setup distinct from ours.

On the other hand, the theory of scaled relative graph (SRG) by Ryu, Hannah, and Yin [38] allows one to analyze the convergence of operator splitting methods by mapping the action of a multi-valued nonlinear operator to the extended complex plane, analogous to how the spectrum maps the action of a linear operator to the complex plane. Follow-up work has extended the theory and applied it to analyze nonlinear operators: Huang, Ryu, and Yin characterized the SRG of normal matrices [25], Pates further characterized the SRG of linear operators using the Toeplitz‚ÄìHausdorff theorem [31], and Huang, Ryu, and Yin [26] established the tightness of the averagedness coefficient of the composition of averaged operators [29] and the DYS operator [18]. SRG has also found applications in control theory: Chaffey, Forni, and Rodolphe utilized the SRG to analyze input-output properties of feedback systems [11, 10], and Chaffey and Sepulchre furthermore used it as an experimental tool to determine properties of a given model[13, 9, 12].

1.2 Contribution and organization

Section¬†2 presents our first major contribution, formalizing an SRG theory for the DYS operator. This result reduces the problem of analyzing the DYS operator into bounding the maximum modulus of a subset of the complex plane. Section¬†3 presents our second major contribution, analyzing contraction factors of the DYS operator. These factors are tighter than those shown in [18] and are, to the best of our knowledge, the best known factors. Finally, Section¬†4 presents a minor contribution, a tight averagedness coefficient of the DYS operator under the assumption of strong monotonicity of or and Lipschitzness of . This is, to the best of our knowledge, the first averagedness result of DYS without cocoercivity of .

The maximum modulus theorem

The remainder of this section proves Theorem¬†2.1 with the following structure. Section¬†2.1 defines the quotient operator and characterizes some useful properties, Section¬†2.2 establishes an SRG product theorem and apply it to the quotient operator, and Section¬†2.3 proves Theorem¬†2.1.

2.2 SRG product theorem

We first establish a product theorem for SRGs, which is of independent interest. This product theorem differs from [38, Theorem¬†7] in that one of operands is a single fixed operator, rather than an operator class. We then apply it to the quotient operator.

3 Contraction factors of DYS

Using the SRG theory of Section¬†2, we prove new contraction factors of DYS in three settings of interest. The three contraction factors of Theorems¬†3.1, 3.2, and 3.3 are strictly smaller (better)than the six contraction factors of [17, Theorem¬†D.6] and are, to the best of our knowledge, the best known rates.

3.1 Proofs of Theorems¬†3.1, 3.2, and 3.3

Before going through proofs, we introduce two elementary Lemmas.

Lemma 3.4.

By simple calculation, we could verify that our six contraction factors are strictly better than those updated prior rates, respectively. The detailed calculations comparing our rates against the prior rates of [17] are carried out in the arXiv version of this paper [27, Section¬†3.2]. In this section, we want to focus on the numerical results of this comparison with the worst-case rate obtained by the performance estimation problem (PEP) framework [20, 43, 39]. For a fair comparison with prior rates, we optimize the choice of œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ and Œ∑ùúÇ\etaitalic_Œ∑ to minimize the factors above and compare with our results. As depicted in Figure¬†1, the contraction factors we derived are much closer to the tight contraction factors evaluated by the PEP approach. In this sense, our contraction factors are a better proxy of the tight contraction factors than the earlier results in [17]. We further investigate the advantages of our rates in assessing the computational cost, especially in an ill-conditioned case where the coefficient of the strong monotonicity Œºùúá\muitalic_Œº imposed to ùíúùíú{\mathcal{A}}caligraphic_A, ‚Ñ¨‚Ñ¨{\mathcal{B}}caligraphic_B, or ùíûùíû{\mathcal{C}}caligraphic_C is infinitesimal. Indeed, these discrepancies are even higher than 4444 in some cases, supporting significant improvement of our results in the sense we are aware of.

3.2.2 Contraction factors of FBS

5 Conclusion

In this work, we extended the SRG theory to accommodate the DYS operator and used this theory to analyze the convergence of DYS iterations. In our view, the SRG theory of Section¬†2 opens the door to many avenues of future work on splitting methods, and the analyses of Section¬†3 serve as demonstrations of such possibilities. One possible future direction is to further refine the analysis on the complex plane and obtain tighter contraction factors, as the contraction factors œÅùúå\rhoitalic_œÅ presented in Section¬†3 are not tight in the sense that

œÅ>sup‚ààùíú,‚Ñ¨,ùíû,Œ±,Œªx,y‚ààdom,x‚â†y‚à•x‚àíy‚à•‚à•x‚àíy‚à•.\rho>\sup_{\begin{subarray}{c}{\varbbT}\in{}_{{\mathcal{A}},{\mathcal{B}},{% \mathcal{C}},\alpha,\lambda}\\ x,y\in\mathrm{dom}\,{\varbbT},\,x\neq y\end{subarray}}\frac{\lVert{\varbbT}x-{% \varbbT}y\rVert}{\lVert x-y\rVert}.italic_œÅ > roman_sup start_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_ARG start_ROW start_CELL ‚àà start_FLOATSUBSCRIPT caligraphic_A , caligraphic_B , caligraphic_C , italic_Œ± , italic_Œª end_FLOATSUBSCRIPT end_CELL end_ROW start_ROW start_CELL italic_x , italic_y ‚àà roman_dom , italic_x ‚â† italic_y end_CELL end_ROW end_ARG end_POSTSUBSCRIPT divide start_ARG ‚à• italic_x - italic_y ‚à• end_ARG start_ARG ‚à• italic_x - italic_y ‚à• end_ARG .

Another direction is to characterize optimal or near-optimal choices of parameters Œ±ùõº\alphaitalic_Œ± and ŒªùúÜ\lambdaitalic_Œª given a set of assumptions on the operators.
